e, United Kingdom","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Anglie","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom","France":"Francie"},"da":{"1384–20 February 1419":"1384–20. februar 1419","1384–1419":"1384–1419","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1402–1422":"1402–1422","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1359–1410":"1359–1410","Bef 1 March 1410":"før 1. marts 1410","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1450":"1450","1359":"1359","1 March 1410":"1. marts 1410","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","about 1402":"omkring 1402","February 1419":"februar 1419","1419":"1419","20 February 1419":"20. februar 1419","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","Grafton, Worcestershire, England":"Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","France":"Frankrig"},"nl":{"1384–20 February 1419":"1384–20 februari 1419","1384–1419":"1384–1419","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1402–1422":"1402–1422","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1359–1410":"1359–1410","Bef 1 March 1410":"vóór 1 maart 1410","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1450":"1450","1359":"1359","1 March 1410":"1 maart 1410","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","about 1402":"circa 1402","February 1419":"februari 1419","1419":"1419","20 February 1419":"20 februari 1419","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","Grafton, Worcestershire, England":"Drayton, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"1384–20 February 1419":"1384–20 February 1419","1384–1419":"1384–1419","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1402–1422":"1402–1422","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1359–1410":"1359–1410","Bef 1 March 1410":"before 1 March 1410","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1450":"1450","1359":"1359","1 March 1410":"1 March 1410","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","about 1402":"about 1402","February 1419":"February 1419","1419":"1419","20 February 1419":"20 February 1419","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","Grafton, Worcestershire, England":"Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stafford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name principally from Stafford (Staffordshire), but occasionally from other places with similar names, such as Stafford House in Ifield (Sussex), possibly East and West Stowford in East Down (Devon), and three minor places in Devon called Stafford, in Dolton, Broadhembury, and Colyton parishes. The places are all named with Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ as the final element, but have different initial elements. The Staffordshire placename has Old English <i>stæth</i> ‘river bank, shore’; Stafford in Colyton (Devon) has Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’; the Sussex placename has Old English <i>stēor</i> ‘steer, bullock’; East and West Stowford (Devon) have Old English <i>stæf</i> ‘staff, stave, rod’; Stafford in Dolton and Stafford in Broadhembury (Devon) may have Old English <i>stæth</i>, <i>stān</i>, or <i>stæf</i>.","Irish (Wexford): variant of   Stocker  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stocker","meanings":["German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>): topographic name for someone living by a tree stump (see   Stock   3) or an occupational name for a tree cutter, from Middle High German <i>stocken</i> ‘to clear land’.","German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>); Dutch: occupational name from Middle High German, Middle Dutch <i>stocker</i> ‘jailer’.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>stokker</i> ‘one who sells stockfish’ (fish dried in the air without salt). This was the usual source of the name in medieval London, where a bylaw of 1419 stated that no <i>stokker</i> should board a ship to buy fish (presumably in order to forestall the market)."]}]},{"name":"Humphrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Humphry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfrey","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Humphrey Stafford was born in 1384, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ralph Stafford, was 29 and his mother, Maud Hastings, was 25. He married Elizabeth Burdett in 1399, in Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. In 1383, his occupation is listed as  member of british parliament for warwichshire, wiltshire, dorset, so